<styl>by <m2>By <m0>INA PAIVA CORDLE<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Business Writer<ql>
<m1><ep>
<m0> Big Brother may be coming to a bank near you.<ep>
  In a pilot program to be launched next month in Dade County, noncustomers who want to cash checks at First Union or SunTrust will be asked to leave their thumbprints along with their signatures.<ep>
  Geared to combat check fraud, the inkless thumbprints will help law enforcement agencies identify criminals who have passed bogus checks. Already in place in Nevada, Arizona and Texas, the program is meant as a deterrent.<ep>
  Early results show some banks have had as much as a 40 percent drop in bad checks since implementing the thumbprinting, said John Milstead, executive vice president of the Florida Bankers Association, which is spearheading the program.<ep>
  And thumbprints on checks may only be the beginning. Technology is being developed to place fingerprint identifiers on the magnetic stripes of credit and ATM cards, said John Hall, spokesman for the American Bankers Association.<ep>
  ``It's for the cardholders' security,'' Hall said.<ep>
  During the trial program, starting in early June, First Union will ask non-account holders to stamp their right thumbprints on the backs of checks they cash. The thumbprinting, which leaves no residue or ink stain, will be used at the bank's 56 Dade branches, said spokesman Ken Darby. After one month, the bank will decide whether to expand it to the rest of the state, he said.<ep>
   Beginning July 1, SunTrust will <m2><ql>
