<m0>require noncustomers to stamp their thumbprints on the front of checks at its 23 branches in Dade, said spokeswoman Melissa Gracey.<ep>
  At both banks, noncustomers who refuse to give their thumbprints will not be allowed to cash checks.<ep>
  Barnett Bank considered joining the pilot but declined, said spokeswoman Jerri Franz. ``We looked at what it would save us versus what it would cost us, and factored in the inconvenience to the consumer,'' Franz said.<ep>
<m0>  <m0>Other banks may join in later, Milstead said.<ep>
  ``If we get the same results in Florida as in other states like Texas, which we fully expect we will, I think you'll see a large percentage of the industry going to this,'' he said.<ep>
  Check fraud is a mounting problem in the state, Milstead said, and it has been particularly heavy during the past year. Florida banks lose as much as $100 million each year because of fraudulent checks, he said.<ep>
  Still unknown is how consumers will respond to the thumbprinting practice.<ep>
  Janice Shields, coordinator of the Consumer Finance Project at Ralph Nader's Center for Study of Responsive Law, in Washington, D.C., said she opposes thumbprinting. She said bank industry figures show that fraud losses amount to one penny per check, of all checks cashed nationwide, or $1.36 per bounced check.<ep>
  ``Is this invasion of privacy necessary when you look at check fraud on a per-check basis?'' Shields asked. ``And there's no control over what could happen to that fingerprint. What's next? DNA samples?''<ep>
  But Milstead isn't worried about a backlash from consumers.<ep>
  ``I think people will understand,'' he said. ``All you're trying to do is be sure you're not giving them real money for a bogus piece of paper.''<ql>
